CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Well--

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:04.850
JOHN BOLTON: We did out of town.

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:06.933
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: We did
the Hartford out of town.

00:08:06.933 --> 00:08:08.750
But I remember, I mean,
we had-- this show

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:10.620
had been kicked around
for quite some time.

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:13.592
I would say about
three years maybe.

00:08:13.592 --> 00:08:15.050
And so there were
lots of readings.

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:18.260
And I'd gone in a few times.

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:21.110
And they'd always say, oh, she's
too young, she's too young.

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:24.850
So my last audition, I was
like, wearing long skirt--

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:27.994
like, I tried to look as old
and mature as-- and they said,

00:08:27.994 --> 00:08:28.910
you're old enough now.

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:30.880
So grateful.

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:32.444
Grateful.

00:08:32.444 --> 00:08:34.460
ZACH ADKINS: I mean,
kind of speak to that.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.620
When you're developing
a musical, it takes--

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:38.010
I mean, I don't think I
know of a musical that

00:08:38.010 --> 00:08:40.500
didn't take at least eight
years to be brought to Broadway.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:40.909
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Yeah.

00:08:40.909 --> 00:08:42.049
ZACH ADKINS: So when
you're doing these readings

00:08:42.049 --> 00:08:45.170
and workshops, a lot of the
projects you work on early on

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:49.370
will take many, many years and
