00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.270
what that sound was.

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:18.980
Because he's progressed
so much as a composer.

00:09:18.980 --> 00:09:20.230
JOHN BOLTON: It's
20 years later.

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:21.813
ZACH ADKINS: He was
like, oh how did I

00:09:21.813 --> 00:09:23.492
write when I was 30-something?

00:09:23.492 --> 00:09:25.700
And it was a really interesting
conversation to have.

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:26.520
JOHN BOLTON: Because
you may know,

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:29.010
they wrote a bunch of new
songs for the stage version.

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:29.630
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: So many more.

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:31.296
JOHN BOLTON: Five or
six from the film--

00:09:31.296 --> 00:09:33.470
ALAN: Yeah and it was 24
new ones or something?

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:34.553
JOHN BOLTON: It's a bunch.

00:09:34.553 --> 00:09:36.530
There's a lot-- things
like reprises and stuff.

00:09:36.530 --> 00:09:37.250
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: So
you think, oh, it's

00:09:37.250 --> 00:09:38.990
just going to be an
exact replication.

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:42.350
There's so much that's
changed and there's so much--

00:09:42.350 --> 00:09:45.320
I mean, if you
love our composers,

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:46.914
the new music is unbelievable.

00:09:46.914 --> 00:09:48.080
JOHN BOLTON: It's beautiful.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:50.262
ALAN: Even the bad guy.

00:09:50.262 --> 00:09:52.220
The bad guy's totally
different from the movie.

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:53.972
So there's no Rasputin, right?

00:09:53.972 --> 00:09:54.930
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Yeah.

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:57.322
There's a handsome,
dark character.

00:09:57.322 --> 00:09:58.447
ALAN: Oh you like him, huh?

00:09:58.447 --> 00:10:00.488
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Well,
there's-- it leaves it up

00:10:00.488 --> 00:10:02.300
to interpretation, you know?

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:05.036
ALAN: I was going to
ask you later if--

00:10:05.036 --> 00:10:06.410
do you want to
set up the context

00:10:06.410 --> 00:10:08.754
for your possible
relationship with--

00:10:08.754 --> 00:10:09.920
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: With Gleb?

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:10.837
ALAN: With Gleb, yeah.

00:10:10.837 --> 00:10:12.545
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
Well, so, what I really

00:10:12.545 --> 00:10:14.210
love about this
musical is that it does

00:10:14.210 --> 00:10:16.310
tie in real Russian history.

00:10:16.310 --> 00:10:20.030
And, as we all know,
during that time period,

00:10:20.030 --> 00:10:22.760
the fall of the
Bolshevik Revolution,

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:26.210
which is where they went from
a monarchy to king and queen

00:10:26.210 --> 00:10:27.620
to communism.

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:31.370
And you have this
guy that's kind

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:34.589
of working his way up the ranks,
this evil character, Gleb.

00:10:34.589 --> 00:10:35.630
And he's not really evil.

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:37.400
He's just a misunderstood guy.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:39.800
His family-- well
I mean, his family.

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:42.170
His dad, you find-- you
come to find out his dad

00:10:42.170 --> 00:10:45.440
was a part of the firing
squad for the Romanov family.

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:47.750
So he has a lot of guilt
inside of him dealing

00:10:47.750 --> 00:10:50.040
with you know, and then,
dealing with his family

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:53.180
and what is honor and
what is the right thing

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:55.430
to do versus the wrong thing
to do when you're ordered

00:10:55.430 --> 00:10:57.260
to kill a bunch of kids?

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:01.010
So so over time,
he runs into Anya.

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:03.310
And then, he kind of
has a crush on her.

00:11:03.310 --> 00:11:05.682
And also, it's kind of like--

00:11:05.682 --> 00:11:08.140
I think-- I feel like it's a
little bit like the hunchback,

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:10.030
where, if you know anything
about the hunchback,

00:11:10.030 --> 00:11:11.440
how it's kind of
like, he loves--

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:13.687
the bad guy loves Esmerelda
but also hates her.

00:11:13.687 --> 00:11:14.770
So it's kind of like this.

00:11:14.770 --> 00:11:17.359
He loves her, but he also wants
to kill her at the same time.

00:11:17.359 --> 00:11:18.400
ALAN: And the Bolsheviks.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:18.850
Yeah.

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:19.140
Yeah.

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:19.390
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Yeah.

00:11:19.390 --> 00:11:21.700
It's like he-- Gleb is in
love with her, but also.

00:11:21.700 --> 00:11:23.080
Yeah.

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:24.620
ALAN: So why-- but
why do you think

00:11:24.620 --> 00:11:26.299
the choice was made
to actually switch

00:11:26.299 --> 00:11:27.340
the character completely?

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:30.250
Just a magical sorcerer
was not going play?

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:32.942
JOHN BOLTON: Well, Rasputin
was not a magical sorcerer,

00:11:32.942 --> 00:11:33.900
for those of you that--

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:34.810
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: The
real Rasputin existed.

00:11:34.810 --> 00:11:36.730
JOHN BOLTON: --that
only know the cartoon.

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:39.245
He wasn't a jolly ne'er do well.

00:11:39.245 --> 00:11:40.870
He was a pretty
despicable human being.

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:44.170
And he was long dead,
actually dead, had

00:11:44.170 --> 00:11:47.860
been taken out by some of the--

00:11:47.860 --> 00:11:50.680
not the Tsar, but those
directly underneath the Tsar.

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:52.660
Because Rasputin was getting--

00:11:52.660 --> 00:11:55.190
was way too close
to the royal family.

00:11:55.190 --> 00:11:59.350
He had the empress, Tsarina
Alexandra, under his thumb,

00:11:59.350 --> 00:12:02.970
in terms of, only I
can take care of you

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:04.567
your young, sick boy.

00:12:04.567 --> 00:12:06.150
Because there were
the four daughters.

00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:09.460
And the youngest boy
was a hemophiliac.

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:12.930
And so Alexandra wanted to
do everything she could.

00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:16.870
And a friend of hers said,
get this mystic guy in.

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:20.151
And all of a sudden, he was
hanging out in the grand

00:12:20.151 --> 00:12:20.650
duchess's--

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:22.910
the daughters'
bedrooms late at night.

00:12:22.910 --> 00:12:25.999
And a lot of the court
said, get him out.

00:12:25.999 --> 00:12:27.040
And so they murdered him.

00:12:27.040 --> 00:12:29.110
They had him brutally killed.

00:12:29.110 --> 00:12:31.659
And so he's-- if you
know the history,

00:12:31.659 --> 00:12:33.700
he's long dead when the
events of the show start.

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:38.770
So I think that was the initial
way to create a more real--

00:12:38.770 --> 00:12:40.440
ALAN: I didn't know
that historically,

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:41.490
that it was different like that.

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:43.390
That makes a lot of
sense to change it up.

00:12:43.390 --> 00:12:43.690
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
And it makes sense,

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:45.106
because the whole
thing is it took

00:12:45.106 --> 00:12:46.254
a long time for him to die.

00:12:46.254 --> 00:12:47.920
Like, cause they think
he's this mystic.

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:49.907
So they kept trying to
kill him in real life,

00:12:49.907 --> 00:12:50.740
and he couldn't die.

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:52.960
So I think they used
that for the cartoon.

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:56.032
It's like kind of a joke that
he's not really dead yet.

00:12:56.032 --> 00:12:57.582
Cause in real life-- anyway.

00:12:57.582 --> 00:13:00.040
ZACH ADKINS: I mean, if you
are a fan of the movie, though,

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:00.691
the theme--

00:13:00.691 --> 00:13:02.440
Rasputin sings "In the
Dark of the Night."

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:04.060
I mean, it comes
up multiple times.

00:13:04.060 --> 00:13:06.160
Actually, it's the theme
of a song called "Stay,

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:08.285
I Pray You" in our show,
which is a beautiful group

00:13:08.285 --> 00:13:11.452
number talking about leaving
your country for the last time.

00:13:11.452 --> 00:13:12.910
And so if you do
come see the show,

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:15.580
and you love Rasputin and
those numbers, they're there.

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:17.740
You have to really,
really key in on that.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:19.110
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Same
thing with "At The Beginning

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:19.740
With You."

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:21.900
Some little underscoring.

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:23.780
ALAN: So the characters
are obviously well

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:25.570
known, both, I
guess, historically,

00:13:25.570 --> 00:13:26.600
and from the movies now.

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.150
Do you find that
people are always

00:13:28.150 --> 00:13:30.010
trying to compare
you, like your roles

00:13:30.010 --> 00:13:33.447
now to what was in the
movies, the characters?

00:13:33.447 --> 00:13:34.780
JOHN BOLTON: Well I think they--

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:39.190
they tend to say that we got it.

00:13:39.190 --> 00:13:42.292
But, you know, I like to
think that we acknowledged

00:13:42.292 --> 00:13:43.375
the character in the film.

00:13:43.375 --> 00:13:45.310
They're animated
characters in the film.

00:13:45.310 --> 00:13:47.770
But certainly, the vocal,
the voice performance

00:13:47.770 --> 00:13:49.860
is what we can take.

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:51.670
Certainly what I took cues from.

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:52.610
Kelsey Grammer's--

00:13:52.610 --> 00:13:52.930
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: We honor it.

00:13:52.930 --> 00:13:53.680
JOHN BOLTON: You honor it.

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:54.220
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: You honor it.

00:13:54.220 --> 00:13:54.719
You don't--

00:13:54.719 --> 00:13:57.490
JOHN BOLTON: But to do a slavish
imitation doesn't serve anyone,

00:13:57.490 --> 00:13:57.989
really.

00:13:57.989 --> 00:13:59.330
And so I honor it.

00:13:59.330 --> 00:14:00.070
And, and--

00:14:00.070 --> 00:14:01.030
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: I honor it.

00:14:01.030 --> 00:14:02.170
JOHN BOLTON: Add my
own stuff into it.

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:03.370
ZACH ADKINS: I think once
you're seeing the show, you

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:04.860
kind of forget it was a movie.

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:06.520
When you're sitting
in the theater,

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:08.470
you know, you come in
with this expectation.

00:14:08.470 --> 00:14:10.170
But once it starts,
we kind of pull you

00:14:10.170 --> 00:14:12.100
in a lot of directions
right at the beginning.

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:15.232
And we send you a million
different directions,

00:14:15.232 --> 00:14:16.440
a million different thoughts.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:18.267
And you don't really
think about, oh wait.

00:14:18.267 --> 00:14:19.600
Well what happened in the movie?

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:20.380
You know?

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:24.430
JOHN BOLTON: It's very much its
own theatrical event as opposed

00:14:24.430 --> 00:14:26.152
to any sort of slavish
recreation of--

00:14:26.152 --> 00:14:27.610
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
Exact recreation.

00:14:27.610 --> 00:14:28.720
JOHN BOLTON: --of
either of the films.

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:29.420
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: It's not.

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:30.070
ALAN: Well yeah.

00:14:30.070 --> 00:14:31.986
I want to talk about the
set too for a second.

00:14:31.986 --> 00:14:33.699
Because the set itself is--

00:14:33.699 --> 00:14:35.490
gosh, I don't even know
how to describe it.

00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:39.934
There's like this
massive arc made of--

00:14:39.934 --> 00:14:42.100
you know, it's supposed to
be this marble thing or--

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:44.740
it's a castle, it's the
city, it's the walkway,

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:47.930
it's all this multi-purpose
set that doesn't move,

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:51.040
but yet rotates and changes.

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:53.319
What was-- like, you guys,
when you first saw it,

00:14:53.319 --> 00:14:54.360
what did you think of it?

00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:55.210
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
That first day.

00:14:55.210 --> 00:14:55.770
JOHN BOLTON:
Absolutely thrilling.

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:57.780
It's basically
508 or something--

00:14:57.780 --> 00:15:00.220
506, 508 TV monitors.

00:15:00.220 --> 00:15:01.860
The entire back wall.

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:05.230
And each monitor is responsible
for its own tiny little piece

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:05.920
of the--

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:07.420
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
The whole picture.

00:15:07.420 --> 00:15:08.200
JOHN BOLTON: --visual puzzle.

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:09.460
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
Like a puzzle, yeah.

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:11.920
JOHN BOLTON: And they're able to
do some really amazing things.

00:15:11.920 --> 00:15:12.910
I believe we're
the only Broadway

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:14.230
show that uses that technology.

00:15:14.230 --> 00:15:15.820
I know it's been used at
Radio City Music Hall.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:17.760
But I believe we're
the first to use it.

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:19.120
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: And do
you remember that first day

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:21.679
that he came in and showed us
what we were going to-- what

00:15:21.679 --> 00:15:22.720
the show was going to be?

00:15:22.720 --> 00:15:24.440
JOHN BOLTON: He would show
it to us on an iPhone.

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:25.840
And then say,
here's what's going

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:27.270
to be happening behind you.

00:15:27.270 --> 00:15:29.020
You know, time it out.

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:29.984
Go!

00:15:29.984 --> 00:15:31.900
But yes, there were days
where they brought us

00:15:31.900 --> 00:15:33.358
all into the audience
and said, you

00:15:33.358 --> 00:15:35.115
need to sit and watch
what's going on.

00:15:35.115 --> 00:15:36.740
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: So
you know how cool.

00:15:36.740 --> 00:15:38.230
JOHN BOLTON: And
it's really amazing.

00:15:38.230 --> 00:15:38.610
CHRISTY ALTOMARE:
It's pretty cool.

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:39.130
JOHN BOLTON: It's
really spectacular.

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:39.640
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Yeah.

00:15:39.640 --> 00:15:41.360
JOHN BOLTON: We do a
really cool view of Paris.

00:15:41.360 --> 00:15:43.526
They actually sent our
videographer, video designer,

00:15:43.526 --> 00:15:47.520
Erin Ryan, went to Paris and
filmed a lot of the locations.

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:49.810
Because Act 2 takes
place all in Paris.

00:15:49.810 --> 00:15:53.290
And they put together this
amazing video sequence

00:15:53.290 --> 00:15:55.180
of a whirlwind
tour through Paris,

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:58.381
including an elevator ride to
the top of the Eiffel Tower.

00:15:58.381 --> 00:16:00.880
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: And you feel
like you're going to the top.

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:01.780
JOHN BOLTON: You're
feel like you're going.

00:16:01.780 --> 00:16:03.670
And the train-- there's
a train ride we take,

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:04.770
which was the trio we--

00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:05.560
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: You feel
like you're on the train.

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:06.460
JOHN BOLTON: It's
on the train, and--

00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:08.470
ALAN: The train itself is
moving and spinning, yeah.

00:16:08.470 --> 00:16:09.100
JOHN BOLTON: Spinning around.

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:10.540
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: And
you're moving with it, yeah.

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:12.581
ALAN: That was probably
one of my favorite scene,

00:16:12.581 --> 00:16:14.440
like that and the
ballet too, the--

00:16:14.440 --> 00:16:16.570
watching the train and
everything moving around it.

00:16:16.570 --> 00:16:18.340
Because like, you
get the perspective,

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:21.010
and the video changes with
the perspective as the train

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:22.080
is-- it's phenomenal.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:23.100
Go see it.

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:24.391
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: It's so cool.

00:16:24.391 --> 00:16:25.290
It's so cool.

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:27.120
ALAN: Yeah, so the costumes too.

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:28.370
Let's talk about the costumes.

00:16:28.370 --> 00:16:28.496
ZACH ADKINS: Oh yeah.

00:16:28.496 --> 00:16:29.260
JOHN BOLTON: Oh my gosh.

00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:29.520
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: Linda Cho.

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:30.400
ALAN: Beautiful.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:31.860
CHRISTY ALTOMARE: So beautiful.

00:16:31.860 --> 00:16:33.840
ALAN: Like, period, accurate.

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:34.730
Amazing.

